Many studies cleared that the essential oils extracted from parts of the plant have strong antimicrobial properties against many pathogens. They explained that because of the occurrence of high levels of phenolic, aldehyde, terpenes, alcohols, and flavonoids compounds such as methyl cinnamate, eugenol, e-cinnamaldehyde, alpha-pinene, citral-a, citral-b, beta-pinene, patchouli alcohol, azadirachtin, 1-8-cineole, pongamicin, and karanjin (
 Prabuseenivasan et al., 2006; 
 Damjanović-Vratnica et al., 2011; 
 Khan and Ahmad, 2011; 
 Lavanya and Brahmaprakash, 2011; 
 Assiri et al., 2016). In addition, many studies on cut flowers were reported that the vascular blockage occurred by bacteria and other microorganisms could decrease water uptake and finally result in stem breaking and petal wilting (
 Vandoorn and De Witte, 1994; 
 Nair et al., 2003).
